04481nam a2200529Ia 9780791485040DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780791485040  a(DE-B1597)684089  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBP173.4b.A45 2004 7aREL0370602bisacsh04a297/.0822221 aSyed, Mohammad Ali, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Position of Women in Islam :bA Progressive View /cMohammad Ali Syed. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (150 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAuthors Note -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tRoles of the Quran and the Hadith in Islamic Law -- tReward and Punishment of the Sexes by God as Prescribed by the Quran -- tOrigin of Men and Women According to the Quran -- tAssessment of Some Alleged Sayings of the Prophet Muhammad (pbuh) -- tRules of Marriage in Islamic Law -- tThe Position of Husband and Wife in Islamic Law -- tRules of Dissolution of Marriage in Islamic Law -- tRights of Custody and Access to Children in Islamic Law -- tFinancial and Economic Provisions for Women in Islamic Law -- tRules Regarding Women as Witnesses in Islamic Law -- tRules Regarding the Seclusion of Women (Purdah) -- tWomen in Politics and as the Head of a State -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aChallenging the conservative framers of Islamic law who accorded a lesser status to women, Mohammad Ali Syed argues that the Quran and the Hadith—the two primary sources of Islamic law—actually place Muslim women on the same level as Muslim men. Syed provides an overview of both sources and explores their respective roles in Islamic law, emphasizing the Quran's role as the supreme authority and questioning the authenticity of some of the alleged sayings of the Prophet Muhammad (pbuh). From these texts, he elaborates women's rights in a variety of areas, including treatment by God; marriage, divorce, financial provisions, and custody of children; coming out of seclusion (purdah), and taking part in social, economic, legal, and political activities. Rather than presenting what is practiced today, the book covers the theoretical position of Muslim women as sanctioned by the Quran and the authentic Hadith and offers a glimpse of the exalted position of honor and dignity enjoyed by Muslim women in the early days of Islam.This well-researched book is made more distinctive by the author's personal experience. Raised in Bengal, India, Syed was inspired by his family, who valued men and women equally. As he grew up, Syed realized that most Muslim women lived very differently than the women of his family. According to the author, his family was egalitarian because his father and male relatives were not only devout Muslims but also very knowledgeable about Islam. This book is a culmination of his lifelong concern for women's rights under Islam.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aWomen in Islam. 0aWomen in the Hadith. 0aWomen's rightsxReligious aspectsxIslam. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women in Religion. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Islam. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Theology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791485040423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791485040/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles